"Boyle D.R.","Iodargyrite as an indicator of arid climatic conditions and its association with gold-bearing glacial tills of the Chibougamau - Chapais area, Quebec",1997,"Canadian Mineralogist","35","1",,"23","34",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0030733923&partnerID=40&md5=8c2d2bae9c6f0a2e5b2c918a78ee4521","Geological Survey of Canada, 601 Booth Street, Ottawa, Ont. K1A 0E8, Canada","Boyle, D.R., Geological Survey of Canada, 601 Booth Street, Ottawa, Ont. K1A 0E8, Canada","The Ag halide mineral, iodargyrite, together with associated minerals chlorargyrite, bromargyrite, and ""embolite"", form a group of secondary minerals that, in terrigenous supergene environments worldwide, are exclusively confined to oxidized sulfide zones formed in arid and semi-arid climates. The presence of iodargyrite in gold-bearing glacial sediments of the Chibougamau - Chapais area of Quebec (first recorded occurrence of this mineral in Canada), together with other indicators of an arid climate, provides cogent evidence of a past arid climate in this region. These indicators include: a) the existence of a deep water table during sulfide ore oxidation of Chibougamau copper deposits, b) the abundance of ""limonite dice"" in glacial tills, indicative of the pseudomorphic replacement of pyrite grains in bedrock formations under arid conditions, c) the abundance of spongy and corroded grains of gold typical of lateritic terranes, and d) the abundance of possibly desert-derived quartzofeldspathic sand formations. The period of aridity is conjectural at this time owing to lack of definitive dating media, but the nature and preservation of weathered profiles in the region strongly suggest a period of aridity in the Tertiary. Arid climatic conditions in this region may coincide with a known global warming period in late Eocene to middle Oligocene times, when the Earth experienced some of its warmest temperatures. However, possible Pliocene arid conditions preceding onset of glacial events cannot be ruled out.","Ag halides; Arid climate; Chibougamau; Climatic mineral indicators; Glacial tills; Gold; Heavy minerals; Iodargyrite; Quebec; Tertiary; Weathering","arid environment; iodargyrite; secondary mineral; silver halide; Tertiary; till; weathering; Canada, Quebec, Chapais; Canada, Quebec, Chibougamau",,,,,,"Allard, G.O., Doré Lake complex and its importance to Chibougamau geology and metallogeny (1976) Québec Ministère des Richesses Naturelles, Rapport, DP-368; Cimon, J., Minimal Pleistocene glaciation in the Chibougamau area, Quebec (1974) Geol. Assoc. Can. - Mineral. Assoc. Can., Program Abstr., 1; Blanchard, R., Interpretation of leached outcrops (1968) Nevada Bur. Mines, Bull., 66; Bonatti, E., Gartner Jr., S., Caribbean climate during Pleistocene ice ages (1973) Nature, 244 (5418), pp. 563-565; Bouillon, J.J., Les Mines Selbaie story - Geology (1990) Can. Inst. Mining Metall., Bull., 83 (936), pp. 79-82; Bowen, R., Oxygen isotopes as climatic indicators (1966) Earth Sci. Rev., 2 (3), pp. 199-224; Boyle, D.R., Geochemistry and genesis of the Murray Brook precious metal gossan deposit, Bathurst Mining Camp, New Brunswick (1995) Explor. Mining Geol., 4, pp. 341-363; Boyle, R.W., Geology, geochemistry, and origin of the lead-zinc-silver deposits of the Keno Hill - Galena Hill area, Yukon Territory (1965) Geol. Surv. Can., Bull., 111; The geochemistry of silver and its deposits (1968) Geol. Surv. Can., Bull., 160; Burgess, J.A., The halogen salts of silver and associated minerals at Tonopah, Nevada (1911) Econ. Geol., 6, pp. 13-21; The halogen salts of silver at Wonder, Nevada (1917) Econ. Geol., 12, pp. 589-593; Calvo, M., Sevillano, E., Famous mineral localities - Hiendelaencina, Spain (1992) Mineral. Rec., 23, pp. 241-249; Chafetz, H.S., Evidence of an arid to semi-arid climate during deposition of the Cambrian system in central Texas, U.S.A. (1980) Paleogeography, 30, pp. 83-95; Chamley, H., Expression of past climate by clay minera